    <etym xml:lang="ru">Вероятно, восходит к иран. %i*kaušaυra-%i от %i*kauš-%i ‘закалывать’,
        ‘убивать’; ср. <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/><w>kuštan</w></mentioned>, <mentioned
            xml:lang="ae"><lang/><w>kaoš-</w></mentioned>. Специфическая семантика „закалывать
        %sсогласно ритуалу%s“ (в отличие от <ref type="xr" target="#entry_argævdyn"/> ‘резать’
        вообще) могла быть результатом контаминации с <mentioned xml:lang="hbo"><lang/><note
                type="comment" xml:lang="ru">(из хазар.) </note><note type="comment" xml:lang="en"
                >() </note><w>kāšer, košer</w><gloss><q>ритуально дозволенное
            мясо</q></gloss></mentioned>.%n<bibl><author>Benveniste</author><ref target="#ref_BSL"
                /><biblScope>LII 36-38</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
    <etym xml:lang="en">It probably traces back to Iranian %i*kaušaυra-%i from %i*kauš-%i
        ‘slaughter’, ‘kill’; cf. <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/><w>kuštan</w></mentioned>,
            <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/><w>kaoš-</w></mentioned>. The specific semantics
        „slaughter %sby ritual%s“ (as opposed to <ref type="xr" target="#entry_argævdyn"/> ‘cut’ in
        general) may have been a result of contamination with <mentioned xml:lang="hbo"><lang/><note
                type="comment" xml:lang="ru">(из хазар.) </note><note type="comment" xml:lang="en"
                >(from Khazar) </note><w>kāšer, košer</w><gloss><q>ritually allowed
            meat</q></gloss></mentioned>.%n<bibl><author>Benveniste</author><ref target="#ref_BSL"
                /><biblScope>LII 36-38</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
